{"title":"NAIL’D R3ACT rear suspension is hidden in Vaast E/1 e-bike to isolate cargo (and rider) from movement","link":"https://bikerumor.com/2021/09/07/naild-r3act-rear-suspension-is-hidden-in-vaast-e-1-e-bike-to-isolate-cargo-and-rider-from-movement/","date":1631028408000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><div role=\"main\"><article id=\"post-270088\" role=\"article\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/BlogPosting\"><section itemprop=\"text\"><p>At first glance, the new Vaast E/1 e-bike doesn’t look like it has any rear suspension at all. Hiding the suspension components seems to be<a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/2021/09/07/scott-patron-eride-long-travel-emtb-boasts-next-level-integration-with-hidden-shock/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> in vogue</a> at the moment, but Vaast has hidden the suspension components for a very specific reason—to isolate the rider and cargo load from the suspension movement.</p><p><iframe loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"675\" data-ezsrc=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/ahCEeapyvyc?version=3&amp;rel=1&amp;showsearch=0&amp;showinfo=1&amp;iv_load_policy=1&amp;fs=1&amp;hl=en-US&amp;autohide=2&amp;start=50&amp;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation\" ezoid=\"0.8257548276539239\"></iframe></p><p>Why would they want to do that? Vaast says it comes down to preventing any additional load from having a detrimental effect on the suspension performance. E-bikes, especially commuter e-bikes, are often loaded up with all kinds of cargo—from kids, to dogs, crates of beer, heavy groceries, whatever you’d normally transport in a car, really. To offer a better ride, the suspension on the E/1 seems to suspend the rider, while the entire frame moves up and down as the rear wheel traces over bumps. The video above helps demonstrate this, which starts at 0:50.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1.jpg\" alt=\"Vaast Nail'd R3act Ground Tracing Suspension\" width=\"934\" height=\"575\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1.jpg 934w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-297x183.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-800x493.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-120x74.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-768x473.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 934px) 100vw, 934px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb28 src ng ngcb28 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1.jpg 934w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-297x183.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-800x493.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-120x74.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100847/Naild-r3act-react-ground-tracing-suspension-vaast-e1-768x473.jpg 768w\"></a></p><p>It’s kind of hard to wrap your head around, but from the video it appears that as you hit a bump, the seat tube assembly which is attached to the motor housing effectively moves downwards (or stays in place as the rear wheel goes upwards). There is a pivot at the back of the motor housing to the “swingarm” (which doesn’t actually swing), and a linkage at the front with a small shock to provide the actual suspension. The result is a claimed 20% reduction in vibration compared to other suspension systems.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features.jpg\" alt=\"Vaast E/1 e-bike features\" width=\"1402\" height=\"770\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features.jpg 1402w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-297x163.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-800x439.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-120x66.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-768x422.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1402px) 100vw, 1402px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb28 src ng ngcb28 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features.jpg 1402w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-297x163.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-800x439.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-120x66.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100849/Vaast-e-1-ebike-features-768x422.jpg 768w\"></a></p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details.jpg\" alt=\"Vaast e/1 details\" width=\"1920\" height=\"1080\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details.jpg 1920w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-297x167.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-800x450.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-120x68.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-768x432.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-1536x864.jpg 1536w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb28 src ng ngcb28 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details.jpg 1920w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-297x167.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-800x450.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-120x68.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-768x432.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100853/Vaast-e1-ebike-details-1536x864.jpg 1536w\"></a></p><p>Aside from the interesting suspension, the E/1 is packed with features to make it commute-ready right out of the box. Powered by the most current Bosch Gen 4 Performance CX Drive with options for a Gates Carbon belt drive and internal gear hubs, a Bosch Powertube 500 battery is hidden in the seat tube making it easily removable. Because the seat tube is designed around the large battery, there is an integrated tool-free height adjust lever instead of a traditional seat post clamp.</p><p>Integrated heavy duty cargo racks are included with Supernova LED lighting, and a Bosch Kiox display is integrated into the stem. Offered only in a step-through frame design, the hydroformed aluminum frame has a low center of gravity and is based around 27.5″ wheels with high volume tires.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options.jpg\" alt=\"Vaast e/1 ebike build options\" width=\"1267\" height=\"714\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options.jpg 1267w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-297x167.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-800x451.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-120x68.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-768x433.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1267px) 100vw, 1267px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb28 src ng ngcb28 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options.jpg 1267w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-297x167.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-800x451.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-120x68.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/07100851/Vaast-e1-drivetrain-options-768x433.jpg 768w\"></a></p><p>The Vaast E/1 will be offered in three build levels starting with a standard Shimano 1×12 derailleur-equipped drivetrain for $7,499. From there, there are two options for internal gear hubs with Gates Carbon belt drives including the Enviolo ST for $8,499 and the Rohloff E-14 Speedhub for $9,999. Bikes should be available in the USA, UK, and EU markets starting on October 1st, 2021.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.vaastbikes.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>vaastbikes.com</em></a></p></section></article></div></div>","author":"Zach Overholt","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"348542e424bf27957a0ccda8beccfbcb4a8ad25a70d97436fb16da2269fc9226","category":"Cycling"}